  <data key="d15">ann.concept-virtue-perfected-by-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it is evident, in accordance with what has been said ( Article 7 ), that it is charity which directs the acts of all other virtues to the last end, and which, consequently, also gives the form to all other acts of virtue : and it is precisely in this sense that charity is called the form of the virtues , for these are called virtues in relation to "informed" acts.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.virtue" target="concept.habit" id="edge.concept.virtue.species_of.concept.habit">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.virtue.species_of.concept.habit</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d8">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d9">virtue</data>
  <data key="d10">species_of</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.habit</data>
  <data key="d12">Habit</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.concept-virtue-species-of-concept-habit-st-i-ii-q055-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore human virtues are habits .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.virtue" target="concept.operative_habit" id="edge.concept.virtue.species_of.concept.operative_habit">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.virtue.species_of.concept.operative_habit</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d8">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d9">virtue</data>
  <data key="d10">species_of</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.operative_habit</data>
  <data key="d12">Operative Habit</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.concept-virtue-species-of-concept-operative-habit-st-i-ii-q055-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently it is essential to human virtue to be an operative habit .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.1 — Does it belong to man to act for an end?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Of actions done by man those alone are properly called " human ," which are proper to man as man . Now man differs from irrational animals in this, that he is master of his actions. Wherefore those actions alone are prop</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.2 — Is this proper to the rational nature?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Every agent, of necessity , acts for an end. For if, in a number of causes ordained to one another, the first be removed, the others must, of necessity , be removed also. Now the first of all causes is the final cause . </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.3 — Are a man's actions specified by their end?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Each thing receives its species in respect of an act and not in respect of potentiality ; wherefore things composed of matter and form are established in their respective species by their own forms. And this is also to b</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a004" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.4 — Is there any last end of human life?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Absolutely speaking, it is not possible to proceed indefinitely in the matter of ends, from any point of view. For in whatsoever things there is an essential order of one to another, if the first be removed, those that a</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a005" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.5 — Can one man have several last ends?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">It is impossible for one man's will to be directed at the same time to diverse things, as last ends. Three reasons may be assigned for this. First, because, since everything desires its own perfection, a man desires for </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a006" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.6 — Does man ordain all to the last end?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Man must, of necessity , desire all, whatsoever he desires, for the last end. This is evident for two reasons. First, because whatever man desires, he desires it under the aspect of good . And if he desire it, not as his</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a007" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.7 — Do all men have the same last end?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">We can speak of the last end in two ways: first, considering only the aspect of last end; secondly, considering the thing in which the aspect of last end is realized. So, then, as to the aspect of last end, all agree in </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001" target="st.i-ii.q001.a008" id="structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q001.contains.st.i-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 — Man's last end</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.1 a.8 — Do all other creatures concur with man in that last end?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As the Philosopher says (Phys. ii, 2), the end is twofold—the end "for which" and the end "by which"; viz. the thing itself in which is found the aspect of good , and the use or acquisition of that thing. Thus we say tha</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.1 — Is there anything voluntary in human acts?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">There must needs be something voluntary in human acts . In order to make this clear, we must take note that the principle of some acts or movements is within the agent, or that which is moved; whereas the principle of so</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.2 — In irrational animals?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), it is essential to the voluntary act that its principle be within the agent, together with some knowledge of the end. Now knowledge of the end is twofold; perfect and imperfect. Perfect kno</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.3 — Can there be voluntariness without any action?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Voluntary is what proceeds from the will . Now one thing proceeds from another in two ways. First, directly; in which sense something proceeds from another inasmuch as this other acts; for instance, heating from heat. Se</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a004" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.4 — Can violence be done to the will?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The act of the will is twofold: one is its immediate act, as it were, elicited by it, namely, "to wish"; the other is an act of the will commanded by it, and put into execution by means of some other power, such as "to w</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a005" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.5 — Does violence cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Violence is directly opposed to the voluntary , as likewise to the natural . For the voluntary and the natural have this in common, that both are from an intrinsic principle; whereas violence is from an extrinsic princip</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a006" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.6 — Does fear cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As the Philosopher says (Ethic. iii) and likewise Gregory of Nyssa in his book on Man (Nemesius, De Nat. Hom. xxx), such things are done through fear "are of a mixed character," being partly voluntary and partly involunt</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a007" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.7 — Does concupiscence cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Concupiscence does not cause involuntariness, but on the contrary makes something to be voluntary . For a thing is said to be voluntary , from the fact that the will is moved to it. Now concupiscence inclines the will to</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006" target="st.i-ii.q006.a008" id="structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q006.contains.st.i-ii.q006.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 — The voluntary and the involuntary</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q006.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.6 a.8 — Does ignorance cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">If ignorance causes involuntariness, it is in so far as it deprives one of knowledge , which is a necessary condition of voluntariness, as was declared above ( Article 1 ). But it is not every ignorance that deprives one</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022" target="st.i-ii.q022.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q022.contains.st.i-ii.q022.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q022.contains.st.i-ii.q022.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 — The subject of the soul's passions</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q022.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.22 a.1 — Is there any passion in the soul?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The word "passive" is used in three ways. First, in a general way, according as whatever receives something is passive, although nothing is taken from it: thus we may say that the air is passive when it is lit up. But th</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022" target="st.i-ii.q022.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q022.contains.st.i-ii.q022.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q022.contains.st.i-ii.q022.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 — The subject of the soul's passions</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q022.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.22 a.2 — Is passion in the appetitive rather than in the apprehensive part?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As we have already stated ( Article 1 ) the word "passion" implies that the patient is drawn to that which belongs to the agent. Now the soul is drawn to a thing by the appetitive power rather than by the apprehensive po</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022" target="st.i-ii.q022.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q022.contains.st.i-ii.q022.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q022.contains.st.i-ii.q022.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 — The subject of the soul's passions</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q022.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.22 a.3 — Is passion in the sensitive appetite rather than in the intellectual appetite, which is called the will?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ) passion is properly to be found where there is corporeal transmutation. This corporeal transmutation is found in the act of the sensitive appetite , and is not only spiritual , as in the sen</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055" target="st.i-ii.q055.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 — The virtues, as to their essence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.55 a.1 — Is human virtue a habit?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Virtue denotes a certain perfection of a power. Now a thing's perfection is considered chiefly in regard to its end. But the end of power is act. Wherefore power is said to be perfect, according as it is determinate to i</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055" target="st.i-ii.q055.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 — The virtues, as to their essence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.55 a.2 — Is it an operative habit?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Virtue, from the very nature of the word, implies some perfection of power, as we have said above ( Article 1 ). Wherefore, since power [The one Latin word 'potentia' is rendered ' potentiality ' in the first case, and '</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055" target="st.i-ii.q055.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 — The virtues, as to their essence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.55 a.3 — Is it a good habit?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As we have said above ( Article 1 ), virtue implies a perfection of power: wherefore the virtue of a thing is fixed by the limit of its power (De Coelo i). Now the limit of any power must needs be good : for all evil imp</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055" target="st.i-ii.q055.a004" id="structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q055.contains.st.i-ii.q055.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 — The virtues, as to their essence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q055.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.55 a.4 — The definition of virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">This definition comprises perfectly the whole essential notion of virtue . For the perfect essential notion of anything is gathered from all its causes . Now the above definition comprises all the causes of virtue . For </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071" target="st.i-ii.q071.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 — Vice and sin considered in themselves</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.71 a.1 — Is vice contrary to virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Two things may be considered in virtue —the essence of virtue , and that to which virtue is ordained. In the essence of virtue we may consider something directly, and we may consider something consequently. Virtue implie</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071" target="st.i-ii.q071.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 — Vice and sin considered in themselves</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q071.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.71 a.2 — Is vice contrary to nature?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), vice is contrary to virtue . Now the virtue of a thing consists in its being well disposed in a manner befitting its nature , as stated above ( Article 1 ). Hence the vice of any thing cons</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071" target="st.i-ii.q071.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 — Vice and sin considered in themselves</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q071.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.71 a.3 — Which is worse, a vice or a vicious act?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A habit stands midway between power and act. Now it is evident that both in good and in evil , act precedes power, as stated in Metaph. ix, 19. For it is better to do well than to be able to do well, and in like manner, </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071" target="st.i-ii.q071.a004" id="structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 — Vice and sin considered in themselves</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q071.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.71 a.4 — Is a vicious act compatible with virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Sin is compared to virtue , as evil act to good habit . Now the position of a habit in the soul is not the same as that of a form in a natural thing. For the form of a natural thing produces, of necessity , an operation </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071" target="st.i-ii.q071.a005" id="structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 — Vice and sin considered in themselves</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q071.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.71 a.5 — Does every sin include action?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The reason for urging this question has reference to the sin of omission , about which there have been various opinions. For some say that in every sin of omission there is some act, either interior or exterior—interior,</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071" target="st.i-ii.q071.a006" id="structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q071.contains.st.i-ii.q071.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 — Vice and sin considered in themselves</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q071.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.71 a.6 — The definition of sin proposed by Augustine (Contra Faust. xxii): "Sin is a word, deed, or desire against the eternal law"</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As was shown above ( Article 1 ), sin is nothing else than a bad human act . Now that an act is a human act is due to its being voluntary , as stated above ( I-II:1:1 ), whether it be voluntary , as being elicited by the</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090" target="st.i-ii.q090.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 — The essence of law</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q090.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.90 a.1 — Is law something pertaining to reason?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Law is a rule and measure of acts, whereby man is induced to act or is restrained from acting: for "lex" [ law ] is derived from "ligare" [to bind], because it binds one to act. Now the rule and measure of human acts is </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090" target="st.i-ii.q090.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 — The essence of law</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q090.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.90 a.2 — The end of law</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), the law belongs to that which is a principle of human acts , because it is their rule and measure. Now as reason is a principle of human acts , so in reason itself there is something which </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090" target="st.i-ii.q090.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 — The essence of law</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q090.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.90 a.3 — Its cause</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A law , properly speaking, regards first and foremost the order to the common good . Now to order anything to the common good , belongs either to the whole people, or to someone who is the viceregent of the whole people.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090" target="st.i-ii.q090.a004" id="structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q090.contains.st.i-ii.q090.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 — The essence of law</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q090.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.90 a.4 — The promulgation of law</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), a law is imposed on others by way of a rule and measure. Now a rule or measure is imposed by being applied to those who are to be ruled and measured by it. Wherefore, in order that a law ob</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a001" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.1 — Without grace, can man know anything?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">To know truth is a use or act of intellectual light, since, according to the Apostle ( Ephesians 5:13 ): "All that is made manifest is light." Now every use implies movement, taking movement broadly, so as to call thinki</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a002" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.2 — Without God's grace, can man do or wish any good?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Man's nature may be looked at in two ways: first, in its integrity, as it was in our first parent before sin ; secondly, as it is corrupted in us after the sin of our first parent . Now in both states human nature needs </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a003" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.3 — Without grace, can man love God above all things?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As was said above ( I:60:5 ), where the various opinions concerning the natural love of the angels were set forth, man in a state of perfect nature , could by his natural power, do the good natural to him without the add</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a004" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.4 — Without grace, can man keep the commandments of the Law?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">There are two ways of fulfilling the commandments of the Law . The first regards the substance of the works, as when a man does works of justice , fortitude , and of other virtues . And in this way man in the state of pe</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a005" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.5 — Without grace, can he merit eternal life?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Acts conducing to an end must be proportioned to the end. But no act exceeds the proportion of its active principle; and hence we see in natural things, that nothing can by its operation bring about an effect which excee</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a006" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.6 — Without grace, can man prepare himself for grace?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The preparation of the human will for good is twofold: the first, whereby it is prepared to operate rightly and to enjoy God ; and this preparation of the will cannot take place without the habitual gift of grace , which</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a007" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.7 — Without grace, can he rise from sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Man by himself can no wise rise from sin without the help of grace . For since sin is transient as to the act and abiding in its guilt, as stated above ( I-II:87:6 ), to rise from sin is not the same as to cease the act </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a008" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.8 — Without grace, can man avoid sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">We may speak of man in two ways: first, in the state of perfect nature ; secondly, in the state of corrupted nature . Now in the state of perfect nature , man , without habitual grace , could avoid sinning either mortall</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a009" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.9 — Having received grace, can man do good and avoid sin without any further Divine help?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 5 ), in order to live righteously a man needs a twofold help of God —first, a habitual gift whereby corrupted human nature is healed, and after being healed is lifted up so as to work deeds meri</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109" target="st.i-ii.q109.a010" id="structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.i-ii.q109.contains.st.i-ii.q109.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 — The necessity of grace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.i-ii.q109.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">I-II q.109 a.10 — Can he of himself persevere in good?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Perseverance is taken in three ways. First, to signify a habit of the mind whereby a man stands steadfastly, lest he be moved by the assault of sadness from what is virtuous . And thus perseverance is to sadness as conti</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.1 — Is the object of faith the First Truth?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The object of every cognitive habit includes two things: first, that which is known materially, and is the material object, so to speak, and, secondly, that whereby it is known , which is the formal aspect of the object.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.2 — Is the object of faith something complex or incomplex, i.e. is it a thing or a proposition?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The thing known is in the knower according to the mode of the knower. Now the mode proper to the human intellect is to know the truth by synthesis and analysis, as stated in I:85:5 . Hence things that are simple in thems</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.3 — Can anything false come under faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Nothing comes under any power, habit or act, except by means of the formal aspect of the object: thus color cannot be seen except by means of light, and a conclusion cannot be known save through the mean of demonstration</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.4 — Can the object of faith be anything seen?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Faith implies assent of the intellect to that which is believed . Now the intellect assents to a thing in two ways. First, through being moved to assent by its very object, which is known either by itself (as in the case</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.5 — Can it be anything known?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">All science is derived from self-evident and therefore "seen" principles; wherefore all objects of science must needs be, in a fashion, seen. Now as stated above ( Article 4 ), it is impossible that one and the same thin</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.6 — Should the things to be believed be divided into a certain number of articles?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">the word "article" is apparently derived from the Greek; for the Greek arthron [Cf. William of Auxerre , Summa Aurea] which the Latin renders "articulus," signifies a fitting together of distinct parts: wherefore the sma</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.7 — These articles: are they of faith for all times?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The articles of faith stand in the same relation to the doctrine of faith , as self-evident principles to a teaching based on natural reason . Among these principles there is a certain order, so that some are contained i</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.8 — The number of articles</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Articles 4 and 6 ), to faith those things in themselves belong, the sight of which we shall enjoy in eternal life , and by which we are brought to eternal life . Now two things are proposed to us to be s</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.9 — The manner of embodying the articles in a symbol</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As the Apostle says ( Hebrews 11:6 ), "he that cometh to God , must believe that He is." Now a man cannot believe , unless the truth be proposed to him that he may believe it. Hence the need for the truth of faith to be </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001" target="st.ii-ii.q001.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q001.contains.st.ii-ii.q001.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 — Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q001.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.1 a.10 — Who has the right to propose a symbol of faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Objection 1), a new edition of the symbol becomes necessary in order to set aside the errors that may arise. Consequently to publish a new edition of the symbol belongs to that authority which is empower</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.1 — Is charity friendship?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. viii, 2,3) not every love has the character of friendship, but that love which is together with benevolence, when, to wit, we love someone so as to wish good to him. If, however, we d</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.2 — Is it something created in the soul?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The Master looks thoroughly into this question in 17 of the First Book, and concludes that charity is not something created in the soul , but is the Holy Ghost Himself dwelling in the mind . Nor does he mean to say that </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Human acts are good according as they are regulated by their due rule and measure. Wherefore human virtue which is the principle of all man's good acts consists in following the rule of human acts , which is twofold, as </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.4 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Acts and habits are specified by their objects, as shown above ( I-II:18:2 ; I-II:54:2 ). Now the proper object of love is the good , as stated above ( I-II:27:1 ), so that wherever there is a special aspect of good , th</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.5 — Is it one virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Charity , as stated above ( Article 1 ) is a kind of friendship of man for God . Now the different species of friendship are differentiated, first of all, in respect of a diversity of end, and in this way there are three</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.6 — Is it the greatest of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Since good , in human acts , depends on their being regulated by the due rule, it must needs be that human virtue , which is a principle of good acts, consists in attaining the rule of human acts . Now the rule of human </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.7 — Is any true virtue possible without it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Virtue is ordered to the good , as stated above ( I-II:55:4 ). Now the good is chiefly an end, for things directed to the end are not said to be good except in relation to the end. Accordingly, just as the end is twofold</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023" target="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q023.contains.st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 — Charity, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.23 a.8 — Is it the form of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">In morals the form of an act is taken chiefly from the end. The reason of this is that the principal of moral acts is the will , whose object and form, so to speak, are the end. Now the form of an act always follows from</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.1 — Is prudence in the will or in the reason?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As Isidore says (Etym. x): "A prudent man is one who sees as it were from afar, for his sight is keen, and he foresees the event of uncertainties." Now sight belongs not to the appetitive but to the cognitive faculty. Wh</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.2 — If in the reason, is it only in the practical, or also in the speculative reason?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. vi, 5) "a prudent man is one who is capable of taking good counsel." Now counsel is about things that we have to do in relation to some end: and the reason that deals with things to b</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.3 — Does it take cognizance of singulars?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3 ), to prudence belongs not only the consideration of the reason, but also the application to action, which is the end of the practical reason. But no man can conveniently</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.4 — Is it virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( I-II:55:3 ; I-II:56:1 ) when we were treating of virtues in general, " virtue is that which makes its possessor good , and his work good likewise." Now good may be understood in a twofold sense: first, </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.5 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Since acts and habits take their species from their objects, as shown above ( I-II:01:3 ; I-II:18:2 ; I-II:54:2 ), any habit that has a corresponding special object, distinct from other objects, must needs be a special h</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.6 — Does it appoint the end to the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The end of moral virtues is human good . Now the good of the human soul is to be in accord with reason, as Dionysius declares (Div. Nom. iv). Wherefore the ends of moral virtue must of necessity pre-exist in the reason. </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.7 — Does it fix the mean in the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The proper end of each moral virtue consists precisely in conformity with right reason. For temperance intends that man should not stray from reason for the sake of his concupiscences ; fortitude , that he should not str</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.8 — Is its proper act command?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is "right reason applied to action," as stated above ( Article 2 ). Hence that which is the chief act of reason in regard to action must needs be the chief act of prudence . Now there are three such acts. The fi</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.9 — Does solicitude or watchfulness belong to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to Isidore (Etym. x), a man is said to be solicitous through being shrewd [solers] and alert [citus], in so far as a man through a certain shrewdness of mind is on the alert to do whatever has to be done. Now t</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.10 — Does prudence extend to the governing of many?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other tha</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.11 — Is the prudence which regards private good the same in species as that which regards the common good?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 5 ; II-II:54:2 ad 1 ), the species of habits differ according to the difference of object considered in its formal aspect. Now the formal aspect of all things directed to the end, is taken from </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.12 — Is prudence in subjects, or only in their rulers?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is in the reason. Now ruling and governing belong properly to the reason; and therefore it is proper to a man to reason and be prudent in so far as he has a share in ruling and governing. But it is evident that </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a013" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a013">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.13 — Is prudence in the wicked?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a013.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is threefold. There is a false prudence , which takes its name from its likeness to true prudence . For since a prudent man is one who disposes well of the things that have to be done for a good end, whoever dis</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a014" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a014">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a014</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a014</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.14 — Is prudence in all good men?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a014.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The virtues must needs be connected together, so that whoever has one has all, as stated above ( I-II:65:1 ). Now whoever has grace has charity , so that he must needs have all the other virtues , and hence, since pruden</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a015" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a015">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a015</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a015</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.15 — Is prudence in us naturally?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a015.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As shown above ( Article 3 ), prudence includes knowledge both of universals, and of the singular matters of action to which prudence applies the universal principles. Accordingly, as regards the knowledge of universals,</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a016" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a016">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.contains.st.ii-ii.q047.a016</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q047.a016</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.47 a.16 — Is prudence lost by forgetfulness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a016.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Forgetfulness regards knowledge only, wherefore one can forget art and science, so as to lose them altogether, because they belong to the reason. But prudence consists not in knowledge alone, but also in an act of the ap</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.1 — What is justice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The aforesaid definition of justice is fitting if understood aright. For since every virtue is a habit that is the principle of a good act, a virtue must needs be defined by means of the good act bearing on the matter pr</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.2 — Is justice always towards another?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:57:1 ) since justice by its name implies equality, it denotes essentially relation to another, for a thing is equal, not to itself, but to another. And forasmuch as it belongs to justice to rectif</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A human virtue is one "which renders a human act and man himself good " [Ethic. ii, 6, and this can be applied to justice . For a man's act is made good through attaining the rule of reason , which is the rule whereby hu</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.4 — Is it in the will as its subject?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The subject of a virtue is the power whose act that virtue aims at rectifying. Now justice does not aim at directing an act of the cognitive power, for we are not said to be just through knowing something aright. Hence t</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.5 — Is it a general virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Justice, as stated above ( Article 2 ) directs man in his relations with other men. Now this may happen in two ways: first as regards his relation with individuals , secondly as regards his relations with others in gener</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.6 — As a general virtue, is it essentially the same as every virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A thing is said to be "general" in two ways. First, by "predication": thus "animal" is general in relation to man and horse and the like: and in this sense that which is general must needs be essentially the same as the </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.7 — Is there a particular justice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 6 ), legal justice is not essentially the same as every virtue , and besides legal justice which directs man immediately to the common good , there is a need for other virtues to direct him imme</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.8 — Does particular justice have a matter of its own?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Whatever can be rectified by reason is the matter of moral virtue , for this is defined in reference to right reason, according to the Philosopher (Ethic. ii, 6). Now the reason can rectify not only the internal passions</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.9 — Is it about passions, or about operations only?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The true answer to this question may be gathered from a twofold source. First from the subject of justice , i.e. from the will , whose movements or acts are not passions , as stated above ( I-II:22:3 ; I-II:59:4 ), for i</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.10 — Is the mean of justice the real mean?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 9 ; I-II:59:4 ), the other moral virtues are chiefly concerned with the passions , the regulation of which is gauged entirely by a comparison with the very man who is the subject of those passio</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.11 — Is the act of justice to render to everyone his own?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Articles 8 and 10 ), the matter of justice is an external operation in so far as either it or the thing we use by it is made proportionate to some other person to whom we are related by justice . Now eac</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058" target="st.ii-ii.q058.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q058.contains.st.ii-ii.q058.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 — Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q058.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.58 a.12 — Is justice the chief of the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">If we speak of legal justice , it is evident that it stands foremost among all the moral virtues , for as much as the common good transcends the individual good of one person . On this sense the Philosopher declares (Eth</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171" target="st.ii-ii.q171.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 — Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q171.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.171 a.1 — Does prophecy pertain to knowledge?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prophecy first and chiefly consists in knowledge , because, to wit, prophets know things that are far [procul] removed from man's knowledge . Wherefore they may be said to take their name from phanos , "apparition," beca</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171" target="st.ii-ii.q171.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 — Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q171.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.171 a.2 — Is it a habit?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As the Apostle says ( Ephesians 5:13 ), "all that is made manifest is light," because, to wit, just as the manifestation of the material sight takes place through material light, so too the manifestation of intellectual </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171" target="st.ii-ii.q171.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 — Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q171.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.171 a.3 — Is it only about future contingencies?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A manifestation made by means of a certain light can extend to all those things that are subject to that light: thus the body's sight extends to all colors, and the soul's natural knowledge extends to whatever is subject</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171" target="st.ii-ii.q171.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 — Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q171.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.171 a.4 — Does a prophet know all possible matters of prophecy?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Things which differ from one another need not exist simultaneously, save by reason of some one thing in which they are connected and on which they depend: thus it has been stated above ( I-II:65:1-2 ) that all the virtue</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171" target="st.ii-ii.q171.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 — Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q171.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.171 a.5 — Does a prophet distinguish that which he perceives by the gift of God, from that which he perceives by his own spirit?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The prophet 's mind is instructed by God in two ways: in one way by an express revelation , in another way by a most mysterious instinct to "which the human mind is subjected without knowing it," as Augustine says (Gen. </data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171" target="st.ii-ii.q171.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q171.contains.st.ii-ii.q171.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 — Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q171.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.171 a.6 — Can anything false be the matter of prophecy?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As may be gathered from what has been said ( 1 and 3 and 5 ), prophecy is a kind of knowledge impressed under the form of teaching on the prophet 's intellect , by Divine revelation . Now the truth of knowledge is the sa</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a001" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a001.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a001.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.1 — Does it belong to man to act for an end?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a001-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But the object of the will is the end and the good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a002" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a002.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a002.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.2 — Is this proper to the rational nature?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a002-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Every agent, of necessity , acts for an end</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a003" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a003.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a003.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.3 — Are a man's actions specified by their end?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a003-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">And either way, human acts , whether they be considered as actions, or as passions , receive their species from the end</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a004" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.4 — Is there any last end of human life?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a004-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Absolutely speaking, it is not possible to proceed indefinitely in the matter of ends, from any point of view</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a004" target="concept.ultimate_end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.ultimate_end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.ultimate_end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.4 — Is there any last end of human life?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.ultimate_end</data>
  <data key="d12">Ultimate End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a004-treated-in-concept-ultimate-end-st-i-ii-q001-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now the principle in the intention is the last end</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a005" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.5 — Can one man have several last ends?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a005-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">It is impossible for one man's will to be directed at the same time to diverse things, as last ends</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a005" target="concept.ultimate_end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.ultimate_end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.ultimate_end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.5 — Can one man have several last ends?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.ultimate_end</data>
  <data key="d12">Ultimate End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a005-treated-in-concept-ultimate-end-st-i-ii-q001-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">First, because, since everything desires its own perfection, a man desires for his ultimate end, that which he desires as his perfect and crowning good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a006" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.6 — Does man ordain all to the last end?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a006-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Man must, of necessity , desire all, whatsoever he desires, for the last end</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a006" target="concept.ultimate_end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.ultimate_end">
