  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.7 — Do all men have the same last end?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.ultimate_end</data>
  <data key="d12">Ultimate End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a007-treated-in-concept-ultimate-end-st-i-ii-q001-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">We can speak of the last end in two ways: first, considering only the aspect of last end</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q001.a008" target="concept.end" id="edge.st.i-ii.q001.a008.treated_in.concept.end">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q001.a008.treated_in.concept.end</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.1 a.8 — Do all other creatures concur with man in that last end?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.end</data>
  <data key="d12">End</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q001-a008-treated-in-concept-end-st-i-ii-q001-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q001.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">ii, 2), the end is twofold—the end "for which" and the end "by which"</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a001" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a001.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a001.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.1 — Is there anything voluntary in human acts?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a001-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">There must needs be something voluntary in human acts</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a002" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a002.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a002.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.2 — In irrational animals?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a002-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), it is essential to the voluntary act that its principle be within the agent, together with some knowledge of the end</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a003" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a003.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a003.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.3 — Can there be voluntariness without any action?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a003-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Voluntary is what proceeds from the will</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a004" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a004.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a004.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.4 — Can violence be done to the will?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a004-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The act of the will is twofold: one is its immediate act, as it were, elicited by it, namely, "to wish"; the other is an act of the will commanded by it, and put into execution by means of some other power, such as "to walk" and "to speak," which are commanded</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a004" target="concept.will" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a004.treated_in.concept.will">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a004.treated_in.concept.will</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.4 — Can violence be done to the will?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.will</data>
  <data key="d12">Will</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a004-treated-in-concept-will-st-i-ii-q006-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The act of the will is twofold: one is its immediate act, as it were, elicited by it, namely, "to wish"</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a005" target="concept.involuntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a005.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a005.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.5 — Does violence cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Involuntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a005-treated-in-concept-involuntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">and in like manner that which is against the will is said to be "involuntary." Therefore violence causes involuntariness.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a005" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a005.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a005.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.5 — Does violence cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a005-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Violence is directly opposed to the voluntary , as likewise to the natural</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a006" target="concept.involuntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a006.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a006.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.6 — Does fear cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Involuntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a006-treated-in-concept-involuntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">xxx), such things are done through fear "are of a mixed character," being partly voluntary and partly involuntary</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a006" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a006.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a006.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.6 — Does fear cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a006-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">xxx), such things are done through fear "are of a mixed character," being partly voluntary and partly involuntary</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a007" target="concept.involuntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a007.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a007.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.7 — Does concupiscence cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Involuntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a007-treated-in-concept-involuntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore the effect of concupiscence is to make something to be voluntary rather than involuntary.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a007" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a007.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a007.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.7 — Does concupiscence cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a007-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Concupiscence does not cause involuntariness, but on the contrary makes something to be voluntary</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a008" target="concept.involuntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a008.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a008.treated_in.concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.8 — Does ignorance cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.involuntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Involuntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a008-treated-in-concept-involuntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">If ignorance causes involuntariness, it is in so far as it deprives one of knowledge , which is a necessary condition of voluntariness, as was declared above ( Article 1 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q006.a008" target="concept.voluntary_act" id="edge.st.i-ii.q006.a008.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q006.a008.treated_in.concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q006.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.6 a.8 — Does ignorance cause involuntariness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.voluntary_act</data>
  <data key="d12">Voluntary Act</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q006-a008-treated-in-concept-voluntary-act-st-i-ii-q006-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q006.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Ignorance is "consequent" to the act of the will , in so far as ignorance itself is voluntary : and this happens in two ways, in accordance with the two aforesaid modes of voluntary ( Article 3 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022.a001" target="concept.passion" id="edge.st.i-ii.q022.a001.treated_in.concept.passion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q022.a001.treated_in.concept.passion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 a.1 — Is there any passion in the soul?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.passion</data>
  <data key="d12">Passion</data>
  <data key="d13">passion</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q022-a001-treated-in-concept-passion-st-i-ii-q022-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">And here we have passion in its most proper acceptation</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022.a002" target="concept.passion" id="edge.st.i-ii.q022.a002.treated_in.concept.passion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q022.a002.treated_in.concept.passion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 a.2 — Is passion in the appetitive rather than in the apprehensive part?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.passion</data>
  <data key="d12">Passion</data>
  <data key="d13">passion</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q022-a002-treated-in-concept-passion-st-i-ii-q022-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As we have already stated ( Article 1 ) the word "passion" implies that the patient is drawn to that which belongs to the agent</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022.a002" target="concept.sensitive_appetite" id="edge.st.i-ii.q022.a002.treated_in.concept.sensitive_appetite">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q022.a002.treated_in.concept.sensitive_appetite</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 a.2 — Is passion in the appetitive rather than in the apprehensive part?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sensitive_appetite</data>
  <data key="d12">Sensitive Appetite</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q022-a002-treated-in-concept-sensitive-appetite-st-i-ii-q022-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now the soul is drawn to a thing by the appetitive power rather than by the apprehensive power: because the soul has, through its appetitive power, an order to things as they are in themselves: hence the Philosopher says (Metaph</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022.a003" target="concept.intellectual_appetite" id="edge.st.i-ii.q022.a003.treated_in.concept.intellectual_appetite">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q022.a003.treated_in.concept.intellectual_appetite</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 a.3 — Is passion in the sensitive appetite rather than in the intellectual appetite, which is called the will?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.intellectual_appetite</data>
  <data key="d12">Intellectual Appetite</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q022-a003-treated-in-concept-intellectual-appetite-st-i-ii-q022-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now there is no need for corporeal transmutation in the act of the intellectual appetite : because this appetite is not exercised by means of a corporeal organ</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022.a003" target="concept.passion" id="edge.st.i-ii.q022.a003.treated_in.concept.passion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q022.a003.treated_in.concept.passion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 a.3 — Is passion in the sensitive appetite rather than in the intellectual appetite, which is called the will?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.passion</data>
  <data key="d12">Passion</data>
  <data key="d13">passion</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q022-a003-treated-in-concept-passion-st-i-ii-q022-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ) passion is properly to be found where there is corporeal transmutation</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q022.a003" target="concept.sensitive_appetite" id="edge.st.i-ii.q022.a003.treated_in.concept.sensitive_appetite">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q022.a003.treated_in.concept.sensitive_appetite</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q022.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.22 a.3 — Is passion in the sensitive appetite rather than in the intellectual appetite, which is called the will?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sensitive_appetite</data>
  <data key="d12">Sensitive Appetite</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q022-a003-treated-in-concept-sensitive-appetite-st-i-ii-q022-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q022.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">This corporeal transmutation is found in the act of the sensitive appetite , and is not only spiritual , as in the sensitive apprehension, but also natural</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a001" target="concept.habit" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a001.treated_in.concept.habit">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a001.treated_in.concept.habit</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.1 — Is human virtue a habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.habit</data>
  <data key="d12">Habit</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a001-treated-in-concept-habit-st-i-ii-q055-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But the rational powers, which are proper to man , are not determinate to one particular action, but are inclined indifferently to many: and they are determinate to acts by means of habits , as is clear from what we have said above ( I-II:49:4 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a001" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a001.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a001.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.1 — Is human virtue a habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a001-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-i-ii-q055-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Virtue denotes a certain perfection of a power</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a002" target="concept.habit" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a002.treated_in.concept.habit">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a002.treated_in.concept.habit</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.2 — Is it an operative habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.habit</data>
  <data key="d12">Habit</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a002-treated-in-concept-habit-st-i-ii-q055-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently it is essential to human virtue to be an operative habit .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a002" target="concept.operative_habit" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a002.treated_in.concept.operative_habit">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a002.treated_in.concept.operative_habit</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.2 — Is it an operative habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.operative_habit</data>
  <data key="d12">Operative Habit</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a002-treated-in-concept-operative-habit-st-i-ii-q055-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently it is essential to human virtue to be an operative habit .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a002" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a002.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a002.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.2 — Is it an operative habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a002-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-i-ii-q055-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Virtue, from the very nature of the word, implies some perfection of power, as we have said above ( Article 1 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a003" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.3 — Is it a good habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a003-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-i-ii-q055-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As we have said above ( Article 1 ), virtue implies a perfection of power: wherefore the virtue of a thing is fixed by the limit of its power (De Coelo i)</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q055.a004" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.i-ii.q055.a004.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q055.a004.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q055.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.55 a.4 — The definition of virtue</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q055-a004-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-i-ii-q055-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q055.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">This definition comprises perfectly the whole essential notion of virtue</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a001" target="concept.sin" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a001.treated_in.concept.sin">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a001.treated_in.concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.1 — Is vice contrary to virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d12">Sin</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a001-treated-in-concept-sin-st-i-ii-q071-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">One of these is " sin ," which is opposed to virtue in respect of that to which virtue is ordained: since, properly speaking, sin denotes an inordinate act</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a001" target="concept.vice" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a001.treated_in.concept.vice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a001.treated_in.concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.1 — Is vice contrary to virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d12">Vice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a001-treated-in-concept-vice-st-i-ii-q071-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">that it is a kind of goodness , the contrary of virtue is " malice ": while in respect of that which belongs to the essence of virtue directly, its contrary is " vice ": because the vice of a thing seems to consist in its not being disposed in a way befitting its nature : hence Augustine says (De Lib</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a001" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a001.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a001.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.1 — Is vice contrary to virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a001-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-i-ii-q071-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Two things may be considered in virtue —the essence of virtue , and that to which virtue is ordained</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a002" target="concept.vice" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a002.treated_in.concept.vice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a002.treated_in.concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.2 — Is vice contrary to nature?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d12">Vice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a002-treated-in-concept-vice-st-i-ii-q071-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), vice is contrary to virtue</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a003" target="concept.vice" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a003.treated_in.concept.vice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a003.treated_in.concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.3 — Which is worse, a vice or a vicious act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d12">Vice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a003-treated-in-concept-vice-st-i-ii-q071-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">A habit stands midway between power and act. Now it is evident that both in good and in evil , act precedes power, as stated in Metaph. ix, 19. For it is better to do well than to be able to do well, and in like manner, it is more blameworthy to do evil , than</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a004" target="concept.vice" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a004.treated_in.concept.vice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a004.treated_in.concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.4 — Is a vicious act compatible with virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vice</data>
  <data key="d12">Vice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a004-treated-in-concept-vice-st-i-ii-q071-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Sin is compared to virtue , as evil act to good habit . Now the position of a habit in the soul is not the same as that of a form in a natural thing. For the form of a natural thing produces, of necessity , an operation befitting itself; wherefore a natural fo</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a004" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a004.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a004.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.4 — Is a vicious act compatible with virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a004-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-i-ii-q071-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Sin is compared to virtue , as evil act to good habit</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a005" target="concept.sin" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a005.treated_in.concept.sin">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a005.treated_in.concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.5 — Does every sin include action?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d12">Sin</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a005-treated-in-concept-sin-st-i-ii-q071-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The reason for urging this question has reference to the sin of omission , about which there have been various opinions</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a006" target="concept.eternal_law" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a006.treated_in.concept.eternal_law">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a006.treated_in.concept.eternal_law</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.6 — The definition of sin proposed by Augustine (Contra Faust. xxii): "Sin is a word, deed, or desire against the eternal law"</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.eternal_law</data>
  <data key="d12">Eternal Law</data>
  <data key="d13">law_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a006-treated-in-concept-eternal-law-st-i-ii-q071-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">the eternal law , which is God's reason, so to speak</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q071.a006" target="concept.sin" id="edge.st.i-ii.q071.a006.treated_in.concept.sin">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q071.a006.treated_in.concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q071.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.71 a.6 — The definition of sin proposed by Augustine (Contra Faust. xxii): "Sin is a word, deed, or desire against the eternal law"</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d12">Sin</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q071-a006-treated-in-concept-sin-st-i-ii-q071-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q071.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As was shown above ( Article 1 ), sin is nothing else than a bad human act</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a001" target="concept.law" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a001.treated_in.concept.law">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a001.treated_in.concept.law</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.1 — Is law something pertaining to reason?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.law</data>
  <data key="d12">Law</data>
  <data key="d13">law</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a001-treated-in-concept-law-st-i-ii-q090-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Law is a rule and measure of acts, whereby man is induced to act or is restrained from acting: for "lex" [ law ] is derived from "ligare" [to bind], because it binds one to act</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a001" target="concept.reason" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a001.treated_in.concept.reason">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a001.treated_in.concept.reason</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.1 — Is law something pertaining to reason?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reason</data>
  <data key="d12">Reason</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a001-treated-in-concept-reason-st-i-ii-q090-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now the rule and measure of human acts is the reason, which is the first principle of human acts , as is evident from what has been stated above ( I-II:1:1 ad 3 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a002" target="concept.beatitude" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a002.treated_in.concept.beatitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a002.treated_in.concept.beatitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.2 — The end of law</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.beatitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Beatitude</data>
  <data key="d13">beatitude</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a002-treated-in-concept-beatitude-st-i-ii-q090-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now the first principle in practical matters, which are the object of the practical reason, is the last end: and the last end of human life is bliss or happiness , as stated above ( I-II:2:7</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a002" target="concept.common_good" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a002.treated_in.concept.common_good">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a002.treated_in.concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.2 — The end of law</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d12">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a002-treated-in-concept-common-good-st-i-ii-q090-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently, since the law is chiefly ordained to the common good , any other precept in regard to some individual work, must needs be devoid of the nature of a law , save in so far as it regards the common good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a002" target="concept.law" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a002.treated_in.concept.law">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a002.treated_in.concept.law</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.2 — The end of law</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.law</data>
  <data key="d12">Law</data>
  <data key="d13">law</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a002-treated-in-concept-law-st-i-ii-q090-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), the law belongs to that which is a principle of human acts , because it is their rule and measure</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a003" target="concept.law" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a003.treated_in.concept.law">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a003.treated_in.concept.law</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.3 — Its cause</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.law</data>
  <data key="d12">Law</data>
  <data key="d13">law</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a003-treated-in-concept-law-st-i-ii-q090-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">A law , properly speaking, regards first and foremost the order to the common good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a004" target="concept.law" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a004.treated_in.concept.law">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a004.treated_in.concept.law</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.4 — The promulgation of law</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.law</data>
  <data key="d12">Law</data>
  <data key="d13">law</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a004-treated-in-concept-law-st-i-ii-q090-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), a law is imposed on others by way of a rule and measure</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q090.a004" target="concept.promulgation" id="edge.st.i-ii.q090.a004.treated_in.concept.promulgation">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q090.a004.treated_in.concept.promulgation</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q090.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.90 a.4 — The promulgation of law</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.promulgation</data>
  <data key="d12">Promulgation</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q090-a004-treated-in-concept-promulgation-st-i-ii-q090-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q090.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Such application is made by its being notified to them by promulgation</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a001" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a001.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a001.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.1 — Without grace, can man know anything?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a001-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">the light of faith or prophecy which is called the "light of grace ," inasmuch as it is added to nature</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a002" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a002.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a002.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.2 — Without God's grace, can man do or wish any good?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a002-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Man's nature may be looked at in two ways: first, in its integrity, as it was in our first parent before sin ; secondly, as it is corrupted in us after the sin of our first parent . Now in both states human nature needs the help of God as First Mover, to do or</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a003" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a003.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a003.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.3 — Without grace, can man love God above all things?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a003-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But in the state of corrupt nature man falls short of this in the appetite of his rational will, which, unless it is cured by God's grace , follows its private good , on account of the corruption of nature</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a004" target="concept.commandments" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a004.treated_in.concept.commandments">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a004.treated_in.concept.commandments</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.4 — Without grace, can man keep the commandments of the Law?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.commandments</data>
  <data key="d12">Commandments</data>
  <data key="d13">precept</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a004-treated-in-concept-commandments-st-i-ii-q109-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">There are two ways of fulfilling the commandments of the Law</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a004" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a004.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a004.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.4 — Without grace, can man keep the commandments of the Law?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a004-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But in the state of corrupted nature man cannot fulfil all the Divine commandments without healing grace</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a005" target="concept.eternal_life" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a005.treated_in.concept.eternal_life">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a005.treated_in.concept.eternal_life</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.5 — Without grace, can he merit eternal life?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.eternal_life</data>
  <data key="d12">Eternal Life</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a005-treated-in-concept-eternal-life-st-i-ii-q109-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now everlasting life is an end exceeding the proportion of human nature , as is clear from what we have said above ( I-II:5:5 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a005" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a005.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a005.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.5 — Without grace, can he merit eternal life?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a005-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">the force of grace</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a005" target="concept.merit" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a005.treated_in.concept.merit">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a005.treated_in.concept.merit</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.5 — Without grace, can he merit eternal life?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.merit</data>
  <data key="d12">Merit</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a005-treated-in-concept-merit-st-i-ii-q109-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence man , by his natural endowments, cannot produce meritorious works proportionate to everlasting life</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a006" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a006.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a006.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.6 — Without grace, can man prepare himself for grace?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a006-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">and this preparation of the will cannot take place without the habitual gift of grace , which is the principle of meritorious works, as stated above ( Article 5 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a007" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a007.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a007.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.7 — Without grace, can he rise from sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a007-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Man by himself can no wise rise from sin without the help of grace</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a007" target="concept.sin" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a007.treated_in.concept.sin">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a007.treated_in.concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.7 — Without grace, can he rise from sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sin</data>
  <data key="d12">Sin</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a007-treated-in-concept-sin-st-i-ii-q109-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Man by himself can no wise rise from sin without the help of grace</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a008" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a008.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.i-ii.q109.a008.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.i-ii.q109.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">I-II q.109 a.8 — Without grace, can man avoid sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-i-ii-q109-a008-treated-in-concept-grace-st-i-ii-q109-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.i-ii.q109.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now in the state of perfect nature , man , without habitual grace , could avoid sinning either mortally or venially</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.i-ii.q109.a008" target="concept.sin" id="edge.st.i-ii.q109.a008.treated_in.concept.sin">
